# =============================================================================
# Acropora OS — Production Environment Variables
# =============================================================================
#
# This file documents every environment variable the running application
# actually reads in production, verified against the source (not just against
# the development .env.example, which has drifted — see the two gaps noted
# below). It is a reference template, not something to `cp` and fill in
# blindly: in Coolify, set these as the application's environment variables
# (grouped per docs/COOLIFY.md), not as a committed .env file. Never commit a
# real .env.production to git.
#
# Tags used below:
#   [REQUIRED]   the app will misbehave or refuse to boot without this
#   [REQUIRED*]  required only if the named feature/integration is enabled
#   [OPTIONAL]   has a safe built-in default; only set to override it
#   [SECRET]     a credential — put it in Coolify's secret store, never in
#                logs, screenshots, or a committed file
#   [DEV ONLY]   must NEVER be set in a production environment
#   [RESERVED]   present for forward-compatibility; no code path reads it yet
#
# See also:
#   docs/DEPLOYMENT.md  — full production deployment process, including the
#                          "first production boot" checklist these variables
#                          feed into.
#   docs/COOLIFY.md      — exactly how these map onto Coolify's environment
#                          variable groups per application.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Core runtime
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# [REQUIRED] Must be exactly "production". A large amount of production-only
# behavior is gated on this: prisma.config.ts refuses to silently fall back
# to a local DB connection string, packages/database/prisma/seed.ts refuses
# to run at all, apps/api/src/auth/auth.service.ts refuses the development
# mock login, and the UNAS connection startup validator (see below) becomes
# active.
NODE_ENV=production

# [REQUIRED] Postgres connection string for the api service. Must be reachable
# from the api container's network (Coolify-managed Postgres resource or an
# external instance) — never point this at a database exposed on a public
# port. Recommend sizing the connection pool explicitly for a small Hetzner
# VM, e.g. append `&connection_limit=10&pool_timeout=10` — see
# docs/DEPLOYMENT.md's Prisma section for sizing guidance.
DATABASE_URL=postgresql://<user>:<password>@<host>:5432/<database>?schema=public&connection_limit=10

# [REQUIRED] Redis connection string, used for health checks today and
# available for future session storage. Must not be reachable from outside
# the internal Docker network.
REDIS_URL=redis://<host>:6379

# [REQUIRED] Port the NestJS api process listens on inside its container.
# Matches the Dockerfile's EXPOSE 3001 and HEALTHCHECK; only change this if
# you also change the Dockerfile/Coolify port mapping together.
PORT=3001

# [REQUIRED] Public origin of the web app. Used by the api for its single
# allowed CORS origin (apps/api/src/main.ts) — must be the real production
# domain, e.g. https://erp.acropora.hu. Never set to "*".
WEB_URL=https://erp.example.com

# [REQUIRED] Internal address the web app's server-side rewrite
# (apps/web/next.config.ts, /api/* -> API_URL) uses to reach the api service.
# Inside Coolify's internal Docker network this is normally the api service's
# internal hostname and port, e.g. http://acropora-api:3001 — NOT the public
# domain, and not proxied through TLS internally.
API_URL=http://acropora-api:3001

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# UNAS integration
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# UNAS is the webshop/catalog system Acropora OS mirrors product and order
# data from (read-only for products; see docs/ARCHITECTURE.md). Two things
# below are load-bearing for whether the API can even start in production —
# read the note before UNAS_CREDENTIAL_ACTIVE_KEY_VERSION carefully.

# [REQUIRED*, SECRET] The UNAS shop API key. Required whenever the
# UnasConnectionSetting row's credentialMode is ENV_FALLBACK — which is what
# every fresh database gets by default (the migration that creates this table
# inserts that row directly). In other words: unless someone has explicitly
# switched credential storage to the database-encrypted mode via the admin
# UI, this variable is effectively required in production.
UNAS_API_KEY=

# [REQUIRED in production, regardless of the above] apps/api's
# UnasConnectionStartupValidator runs only when NODE_ENV=production, and it
# unconditionally validates the active UNAS master key — even if the
# connection is using ENV_FALLBACK mode and never actually decrypts anything
# with it. Miss this and the API will fail its onModuleInit() and crash-loop
# on every single boot, not just when UNAS features are used. Generate the
# key with: openssl rand -base64 32
UNAS_CREDENTIAL_ACTIVE_KEY_VERSION=1
# [REQUIRED in production, SECRET] Exactly 32 random bytes, base64-encoded,
# matching the active version number above (the variable name's suffix,
# "V1", must match UNAS_CREDENTIAL_ACTIVE_KEY_VERSION). Keep old *_V<n>
# variables around, unset, if you ever rotate — the code looks them up
# dynamically by version to support in-flight rotation.
UNAS_CREDENTIAL_MASTER_KEY_V1=

# [OPTIONAL] Default already points at UNAS's production API; only override
# for a UNAS sandbox/staging shop.
UNAS_API_URL=https://api.unas.eu/shop

# [OPTIONAL] Feature flags for the in-process background sync schedulers.
# Each *_ENABLED defaults to disabled (safe) if unset. Reminder from
# docs/PRODUCTION-DEPLOYMENT-ARCHITECTURE-REVIEW.md: these run inside the
# same process as the HTTP server and are NOT safe to duplicate across
# multiple api replicas — keep api at one replica while any of these are on.
UNAS_PRODUCT_SYNC_ENABLED=false
UNAS_PRODUCT_SYNC_INTERVAL_MINUTES=15
UNAS_PRODUCT_SYNC_STARTUP_DELAY_SECONDS=30
UNAS_CUSTOMER_SYNC_ENABLED=false
UNAS_CUSTOMER_SYNC_INTERVAL_MINUTES=15
UNAS_CUSTOMER_SYNC_STARTUP_DELAY_SECONDS=30
# Missing from the development .env.example today (a documentation gap, not
# a code gap) — this scheduler exists and reads these two variables:
UNAS_ORDER_SYNC_ENABLED=false
UNAS_ORDER_SYNC_INTERVAL_MINUTES=5
UNAS_ORDER_SYNC_STARTUP_DELAY_SECONDS=30

# [RESERVED, not yet wired to any code path] Present for the webhook-based
# alternative to polling, once/if that ships. Safe to leave unset.
UNAS_WEBHOOK_SECRET=

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NAV Online Számla (tax authority) integration
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Used for company-data lookups (queryTaxpayer) and domestic incoming-invoice
# queries (queryInvoiceDigest/queryInvoiceData). Unlike UNAS above, these
# credentials are checked lazily at the point of use (ServiceUnavailableException
# with code NAV_NOT_CONFIGURED), not at boot — so the API will start fine
# without them, but every NAV-dependent request/scheduled run will fail until
# they're set.

# [REQUIRED*, SECRET] Required if any NAV feature is used.
NAV_TECHNICAL_USER_LOGIN=
NAV_TECHNICAL_USER_PASSWORD=
# [REQUIRED*] Your own company's 8-digit tax number (törzsszám) that owns the
# technical user above. Sensitive but not a credential in the same sense as
# the password/sign key; still avoid logging it.
NAV_TECHNICAL_USER_TAX_NUMBER=
# [REQUIRED*, SECRET]
NAV_TECHNICAL_USER_SIGN_KEY=

# [REQUIRED*] Your own software's registered identifier and developer contact
# details with NAV — required by their API contract whenever any NAV feature
# is used, not really "secret" but must be exactly correct.
NAV_SOFTWARE_ID=
NAV_SOFTWARE_DEV_NAME=
NAV_SOFTWARE_DEV_CONTACT=
NAV_SOFTWARE_DEV_TAX_NUMBER=

# [OPTIONAL] Sensible defaults already in code.
NAV_SOFTWARE_NAME=Acropora OS
NAV_SOFTWARE_VERSION=1.0
NAV_SOFTWARE_DEV_COUNTRY_CODE=HU

# [OPTIONAL] Defaults to NAV's live production endpoint. Override only to
# point at NAV's public test system:
#   NAV_API_URL=https://api-test.onlineszamla.nav.gov.hu/invoiceService/v3
NAV_API_URL=https://api.onlineszamla.nav.gov.hu/invoiceService/v3

# [OPTIONAL] Domestic incoming-invoice sync scheduler. Same single-replica
# caveat as the UNAS schedulers above. Missing from the development
# .env.example today (documentation gap, not a code gap).
NAV_INVOICE_SYNC_ENABLED=false
NAV_INVOICE_SYNC_INTERVAL_MINUTES=15
NAV_INVOICE_SYNC_STARTUP_DELAY_SECONDS=30

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Other external API overrides (all optional — safe production defaults exist)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# [OPTIONAL] VIES (EU VAT number validation). Override only for a mock/test
# endpoint.
VIES_API_URL=

# [OPTIONAL] MNB (Hungarian National Bank) official exchange rate feed, used
# for purchase-invoice currency conversion. Known limitation, unrelated to
# this configuration: MNB's own bot protection currently blocks this in
# production (see docs/CURRENT_STATUS.md) — manual rate entry is the
# documented workaround until that's resolved upstream.
MNB_API_URL=

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Reserved — not yet wired to any code path
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# These exist in the development .env.example as forward-looking placeholders
# for a future real authentication provider (see
# docs/PRODUCTION-DEPLOYMENT-ARCHITECTURE-REVIEW.md, Section 2A) and for the
# not-yet-started Számlázz.hu integration (ADR-005). Grepping the codebase
# confirms zero non-test references today. Leave unset; do not treat their
# presence in the dev example as evidence they're load-bearing.
APP_URL=
SESSION_SECRET=
JWT_SECRET=
AUTH_PROVIDER=
SZAMLAZZ_AGENT_KEY=
SZAMLAZZ_API_URL=
SZAMLAZZ_INVOICE_PREFIX=

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Development/CI only — must NEVER be set in production
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# [DEV ONLY] Opt-in flags for slow integration test suites that hit a real
# database. Not read by any runtime application code, only by test files.
# Do not set these in any production or production-adjacent environment.
# RUN_DB_INTEGRATION=1
# RUN_BRAND_INTEGRATION=1
